Dataset and intentions¶

In this episode of Leo analytics, we take a look at data taken in 1986 surrounding the Chernobyl nuclear accident. I took the set from Kaggle.com from this link: https://www.kaggle.com/lsind18/chernobyl-data-air-concentration. Around 2 000 records and 11 variables make up the set. These data deal with measurements of air concentrations of dangerous radioactive isotopes found in european countries. We intend to use geographic Python packages to visualize and further understand these concentrations. But first, some background.

Background on the affair¶

The year 1986 and early morning of April 26 find you sleeping better than a baby. Until something wakes you up. You look at the clock: 1:24 AM. You shuffle to the kitchen to drink water. On the way, a strange glow flows through one of your windows. Half asleep, you ignore it and continue on the water journey. Your mind, lubricated with H20 ventures into the glow as if drawn. What could it be?

During the early moments of the incident, the what could it be question taunted workers at the nuclear power plant, political powers, and civilians living in Pripyat, Ukraine. The population of Pripyat (~49,000) dedicated itself to servicing the nearby nuclear plant. Engineers working at the plant during the incident knew something smelled fishy the moment a giant explosion rocked the plant, and the roof caught fire. Political types knew it was major uh oh times when the engineers reported the explosion. Fire trucks skirting to the plant and bright lights coming from the plant alerted civilians that all was not good in the hood.

No one, however, realized how bad it was. Mismanagement at the plant toned down the severity of the accident. The chief engineer reported a test gone bad, but that only the roof was on fire. The local government, called an emergency meeting, said no problemo my friends we're good, we're handling it.

But then firefighters responders started flowing into hospitals. They showed radioactive burns. Also, maxed out radioactive readings, and inspections of the nuclear plant let to the unpleasant truth - the nuclear core of the plant had exploded.

Evacuations of Pripyat and all inhabitated areas at a 30km radius of the plant followed. Chernobyl (~14, 000 people), lay just 15km below Pripyat, and would become synonymous with the accident.

During a time when the U.S.S.R. wanted to display power, competence, and overall on top of shit-ed-ness, this sort of event proved more than mildly unpleasant. At first, officials tried to keep a hush hush approach, but as nuclear fall out started flowing into the atmosphere flying into surrounding countries, it became clear that the world would know, no matter what.

The affair wreaked enormous damage on the environment and population. Gorbachev, the leader of the Soviet Union at the time, went so far as to say it was the real reason behind the collapse of the Soviet Union.

Our data¶

Remember how nuclear fallout started flying into other countries? This is what our data measures. Our data contains measurements of three radioactive isotopes Iodine 131, Cesium 134, and Cesium 137 sampled in 17 different european countries. Measurements started on April 28, 1986 and continued until August 3, 1986.

Without further ado, let's import the necessary packages and read in our data.

A boring map¶

Originally, my sole desire was to plot samples on a static map. I wanted to agglomerate, so to speak, each country's points and visualize their spread on a map of continental europe.

This turned out harder than I thought.

I started by preprocessing the data. This means massaging variables into the correct formats, checking missing values, and changing variable names to be more readable. You can see the specifics in the Preprocessing jupyter notebook.

Then, I hit the hard stuff. I started to place measurements on maps, but the measurements didn't make sense. Plots taunted me with weird readings, and eventually I found out that the data needed further preprocessing. For example, the latitude and longitude coordinates used to keep track of measurements were swapped in the original dataset. Some cities had no coordinates, and non-european countries showed up on my plots that had no business being there (e.g. Australia). You can participate in these adventures by looking at the Journey jupyter notebook.

So I got here and thought about how the journey was better than the destination. Yes, I could see the spread of sample measurements, but the map smelled like a boring lecture. And, now that I had a visual spread of the samples more ambitious Slytherin thoughts took hold of me.

An interesting map¶

Instead of just seeing where the samples were taken, what if we could see how these measurements changed over time? The first map is ugly. What if we made it prettier? And what if we added zooming capabilities to the map? Seized by these questions, I discovered a delightful Python package named folium to aid in this new endeavor.

In [9]:
import folium
In [10]:
# Where to center the map
CENTRAL_COORDS = [49.30481, 10.5931]     # latitude is the first coordinate
ZOOM_START = 3
In [11]:
i131_map = uf.create_folium_map( 'i131', air, CENTRAL_COORDS, ZOOM_START )

Lo and behold, a dynamic map of Iodine 131 conentration measurements. As a bonus, I even placed Pripyat and Chernobyl on the map (blue and gray circles).

In [12]:
i131_map
Out[12]:

Of course, now you don't need Netflix because you've got this map. Pressing play forwards the measurements in time showing how they change. The legend at the top right gives an idea of how intense the conentration is at the sampling site. You can stop at any point,\ and click on the points to get more information on that particular point.
